    <h2 id="maintenance-tips">Commercial Fridge Maintenance Tips</h2>

    <p>A well-maintained commercial fridge lasts 10–15 years. A neglected one fails in 4–5 years. Here are the essential maintenance practices that every shop owner should follow:</p>

    <h3>1. Clean the Condenser Coils Every 30 Days</h3>
    <p>The condenser coils (usually located at the back or bottom of the unit) release heat from the refrigeration cycle. When these coils get coated in dust, grease, or lint, the compressor has to work much harder — increasing electricity consumption by 15–25% and shortening compressor life.</p>
    <p><strong>How to clean:</strong> Turn off the unit. Use a stiff brush or vacuum cleaner to remove dust from the coils. For greasy buildup (common in restaurant kitchens), use a coil cleaning spray (available at HVAC supply shops for ₹200–₹400 per can). Allow the coils to dry completely before turning the unit back on.</p>

    <h3>2. Inspect and Replace Door Gaskets</h3>
    <p>Door gaskets (the rubber seals around the door frame) are the most overlooked maintenance item. A worn or cracked gasket lets warm, humid air enter the fridge continuously, causing ice buildup on the evaporator, increased electricity consumption, and temperature fluctuations.</p>
    <p><strong>The paper test:</strong> Close the door on a piece of paper. If you can pull the paper out easily, the gasket needs replacement. Replacement gaskets cost ₹500–₹2,000 depending on the model and are easy to install (most push into a channel — no tools required).</p>

    <h3>3. Temperature Calibration</h3>
    <p>Commercial fridge thermostats can drift over time. Use an independent digital thermometer (₹300–₹800 for a good one) placed inside the fridge to verify the actual temperature matches the set temperature. Check monthly. If there's a significant deviation (more than 2°C), call a technician for thermostat recalibration.</p>

    <h3>4. Defrost Schedule (Manual Defrost Units)</h3>
    <p>If your unit has manual defrost, set a schedule — typically every 2–4 weeks, or when ice buildup on the evaporator exceeds 5mm. Heavy ice buildup acts as insulation on the evaporator, reducing cooling efficiency by up to 40%.</p>

    <h3>5. Level the Unit</h3>
    <p>An unlevel fridge causes the door to hang improperly (creating seal gaps) and can affect refrigerant flow. Use a spirit level to check. Most commercial fridges have adjustable feet or castor wheels with levelling screws.</p>

    <h3>6. Keep the Interior Clean</h3>
    <p>Wipe down interior surfaces weekly with a mild food-safe sanitizer. Clean up spills immediately — they become breeding grounds for bacteria and mould. Remove expired products promptly. A clean fridge not only maintains food safety standards (essential for FSSAI compliance) but also runs more efficiently because airflow isn't obstructed.</p>

    <h3>7. Annual Professional Service</h3>
    <p>Once a year, have a qualified refrigeration technician perform a full service: refrigerant gas pressure check, compressor current draw test, fan motor inspection, thermostat calibration, and electrical connection tightening. This costs ₹1,500–₹3,000 per unit and is the best insurance against unexpected breakdowns.</p>

